Azerbaijan, officially the Republic of Azerbaijan, is a [transcontinental](/Boundaries_between_the_continents) nation, straddling the boundary of Western Asia and Eastern Europe. It’s a part of the [South Caucasus](/South_Caucasus) region, a place where tectonic plates of geography and culture grind against each other. To its east lies the vast, shimmering expanse of the [Caspian Sea](/Caspian_Sea). To the north, the rugged republic of [Dagestan](/Dagestan). To the northwest, the ancient land of [Georgia](/Georgia_(country)). To the west, both [Armenia](/Armenia) and [Turkey](/Turkey), and to the south, the imposing presence of [Iran](/Iran). Its capital, and its largest city, is [Baku](/Baku), a city that wears its history like a well-worn leather jacket.

The land that is now Azerbaijan has seen empires rise and fall. It was once under the sway of [Caucasian Albania](/Caucasian_Albania), then various [Persian empires](/Persian_empires). For centuries, it remained tethered to [Qajar Iran](/Qajar_Iran). But history, as it often does, intervened. The Russo-Persian wars of [1804–1813](/Russo-Persian_War_(1804%E2%80%9313)) and [1826–1828](/Russo-Persian_War_(1826%E2%80%931828)) were the brutal architects of change, forcing the Qajar Empire to cede its Caucasian territories to the [Russian Empire](/Russian_Empire). The borders, etched by treaties like [Gulistan](/Treaty_of_Gulistan) in 1813 and [Turkmenchay](/Treaty_of_Turkmenchay) in 1828, solidified the division that persists to this day. The territory north of the [Aras river](/Aras_(river)), once part of Iran, was absorbed by Russia, administered as part of the [Caucasus Viceroyalty](/Caucasus_Viceroyalty_(1801%E2%80%931917)).

By the close of the 19th century, a distinct [Azerbaijani national identity](/Azerbaijani_national_identity) began to coalesce. In 1918, a year after the [Russian Revolution](/Russian_Revolution) shattered the Tsarist autocracy, the [Azerbaijan Democratic Republic](/Azerbaijan_Democratic_Republic) declared its independence from the [Transcaucasian Democratic Federative Republic](/Transcaucasian_Democratic_Federative_Republic). It stood as the first [secular](/Secularity) democratic state in the [Muslim world](/Muslim_world). But the winds of change were fierce. In 1920, the country was absorbed into the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union) as the [Azerbaijan SSR](/Azerbaijan_Soviet_Socialist_Republic). The modern Republic of Azerbaijan eventually reclaimed its sovereignty on 30 August 1991, just before the [dissolution of the Soviet Union](/Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union).

The path to independence was not smooth. In September 1991, the [Nagorno-Karabakh](/Nagorno-Karabakh_Autonomous_Oblast) region, with its ethnic [Armenian](/Armenians) majority, declared the self-proclaimed [Republic of Artsakh](/Republic_of_Artsakh). This de facto independence solidified after the [First Nagorno-Karabakh War](/First_Nagorno-Karabakh_War) concluded in 1994. Despite international recognition placing the region and its surrounding [seven districts](/Armenian-occupied_territories_surrounding_Nagorno-Karabakh) within Azerbaijan's borders, the conflict simmered. The [Second Nagorno-Karabakh War](/Second_Nagorno-Karabakh_War) in 2020 saw the return of those seven districts and parts of Nagorno-Karabakh to Azerbaijani control. A subsequent [Azerbaijani offensive in 2023](/2023_Azerbaijani_offensive_in_Nagorno-Karabakh) effectively ended the Republic of Artsakh and led to the [flight of Nagorno-Karabakh Armenians](/Flight_of_Nagorno-Karabakh_Armenians).

Azerbaijan operates as a [unitary](/Unitary_state) [semi-presidential](/Semi-presidential_system) republic. [4] It is one of the six independent Turkic states, actively participating in the [Organization of Turkic States](/Organization_of_Turkic_States) and the [TÜRKSOY](/International_Organization_of_Turkic_Culture) community. The country maintains diplomatic ties with 182 nations and is a member of 38 international organizations, including the United Nations, the [Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe), the [Non-Aligned Movement](/Non-Aligned_Movement), the [OSCE](/Organization_for_Security_and_Co-operation_in_Europe), and participates in [NATO](/NATO)'s [PfP](/Partnership_for_Peace) program. It’s a founding member of [GUAM](/GUAM_Organization_for_Democracy_and_Economic_Development) and the [Commonwealth of Independent States](/Commonwealth_of_Independent_States), [24] and is an observer state at the [World Trade Organization](/World_Trade_Organization).

The religious landscape is predominantly Muslim, with approximately 97% of the population adhering to Islam. [25] [26] The [Constitution of Azerbaijan](/Constitution_of_Azerbaijan) upholds secularism, with no official state religion. Azerbaijan is classified as a [developing country](/Developing_country) and ranks 89th on the [Human Development Index](/Human_Development_Index). The ruling [New Azerbaijan Party](/New_Azerbaijan_Party), in power since 1993, has faced accusations of authoritarianism under the leadership of presidents [Heydar Aliyev](/Heydar_Aliyev) and his son, [Ilham Aliyev](/Ilham_Aliyev). The Aliyev dynasty’s tenure has drawn criticism regarding Azerbaijan's [human rights record](/Human_rights_in_Azerbaijan), including [media restrictions](/Media_freedom_in_Azerbaijan) and the treatment of its [Shia Muslim population](/Islam_in_Azerbaijan). [27]

### Etymology

• Further information: [Atropatene](/Atropatene), [Caucasian Albania](/Caucasian_Albania), and [Azerbaijan (toponym)](/Azerbaijan_(toponym))

The name "Azerbaijan" traces its origins back to [Atropates](/Atropates), a [Persian](/Persians) [satrap](/Satrap) serving the [Achaemenid Empire](/Achaemenid_Empire). He was later reinstated by [Alexander the Great](/Alexander_the_Great) as the satrap of [Media](/Medes). [28] [29] The name’s deeper roots are believed to lie in [Zoroastrianism](/Zoroastrianism), the ancient religion once dominant in the region. Within the [Avesta](/Avesta), specifically the Frawardin [Yasht](/Yasht) ("Hymn to the Guardian Angels"), a phrase appears: *âterepâtahe ashaonô fravashîm ýazamaide*. This translates from [Avestan](/Avestan) to "we worship the [fravashi](/Fravashi) of the holy [Atropatene](/Atropatene)". [34] The name itself, "Atropates," is a Greek rendering of an [Old Iranian](/Iranian_languages) term, likely [Median](/Median_language), meaning "Protected by the (Holy) Fire" or "The Land of the (Holy) Fire." [35] This name, recorded by [Diodorus Siculus](/Diodorus_Siculus) and [Strabo](/Strabo), evolved over millennia, transforming into *Āturpātākān* in [Middle Persian](/Middle_Persian), then *Ādharbādhagān*, *Ādhorbāygān*, *Āzarbāydjān* in [New Persian](/Persian_language), eventually becoming the modern Azerbaijan. [36]

The name "Azerbaijan" was officially adopted by the [Musavat](/Musavat) government in 1918, following the [collapse of the Russian Empire](/Russian_Revolution) and the establishment of the independent [Azerbaijan Democratic Republic](/Azerbaijan_Democratic_Republic). [37] Prior to this, the designation had been exclusively used for the adjacent region of contemporary northwestern Iran. [38] [39] [40] [41] The territory that constituted the Azerbaijan Democratic Republic was previously known by names such as [Arran](/Arran_(Caucasus)) and [Shirvan](/Shirvan). [42] This naming choice prompted a protest from Iran. [43]

During the Soviet era, the country's name was rendered in Latin script based on the [Russian transliteration](/Russian_transliteration) as *Azerbaydzhan* (Russian: Азербайджа́н). [44] Between 1940 and 1991, it was written in [Cyrillic script](/Cyrillic_script) as Азәрбајҹан.

### History

• Main article: [History of Azerbaijan](/History_of_Azerbaijan)

#### Antiquity

• Further information: [Caucasian Albania](/Caucasian_Albania)

[Petroglyphs](/Petroglyph) in [Gobustan National Park](/Gobustan_National_Park) dating back to the [10th millennium BC](/10th_millennium_BC), suggesting a vibrant early culture.

The earliest traces of human habitation within the territory of Azerbaijan date back to the late [Stone Age](/Stone_Age), linked to the [Guruchay culture](/Guruchay_culture) found in [Azykh Cave](/Azykh_Cave). [45] Early inhabitants included the [Scythians](/Scythia) around the 9th century BC. [35] Following them, Iranian [Medes](/Medes) established dominance south of the [Aras river](/Aras_(river)). [33] The Medes forged a significant empire between 900 and 700 BC, which was subsequently integrated into the [Achaemenid Empire](/Achaemenid_Empire) around 550 BC. [46] The Achaemenid conquest facilitated the spread of [Zoroastrianism](/Zoroastrianism) throughout the region. [47]

##### From the Sasanian period to the Safavid period

The [Maiden Tower](/Maiden_Tower_(Baku)) and the [Palace of the Shirvanshahs](/Palace_of_the_Shirvanshahs) in Baku's [Old City](/Old_City_(Baku), UNESCO [World Heritage Site](/World_Heritage_Site), dating from the 11th–12th centuries.

The [Sasanian Empire](/Sasanian_Empire) incorporated [Caucasian Albania](/Caucasian_Albania) as a [vassal state](/Vassal_state) in 252 AD. King [Urnayr](/Urnayr) officially sanctioned Christianity as the state religion in the 4th century. [48] Despite Sasanian suzerainty, Caucasian Albania persisted as a distinct entity until the 9th century, remaining subordinate to Sasanid Iran and retaining its monarchy. Although a primary vassal of the Sasanian emperor, the Albanian king held limited authority; the Sasanian [marzban](/Marzban) (military governor) wielded the majority of civil, religious, and military power. [49]

During the first half of the 7th century, Caucasian Albania, under Sasanian vassalage, came under nominal Muslim rule following the [Muslim conquest of Persia](/Muslim_conquest_of_Persia). The [Umayyad Caliphate](/Umayyad_Caliphate) repelled both Sasanian and [Byzantine](/Byzantine_Empire) forces from the [South Caucasus](/South_Caucasus), subsequently establishing Caucasian Albania as a vassal state after suppressing Christian resistance led by King [Juansher](/Juansher) in 667. The power vacuum created by the decline of the [Abbasid Caliphate](/Abbasid_Caliphate) was filled by various local dynasties, including the [Sallarids](/Sallarid_dynasty), [Sajids](/Sajid_dynasty), and [Shaddadids](/Shaddadids). In the early 11th century, waves of migrating [Oghuz Turks](/Oghuz_Turks) from Central Asia began to seize control of the territory. At that time, they adopted the [Turkoman](/Turkoman_(ethnonym)) [ethnonym](/Ethnonym). [50] The first Turkic dynasty to establish a significant presence was the [Seljuk Empire](/Seljuk_Empire), which entered the region by 1067. [51]

The pre-Turkic populations spoke a variety of [Indo-European](/Indo-European_languages) and Caucasian languages. Among these were [Armenian](/Armenian_language) [52] [53] [54] [55] [56] and an [Iranian language](/Iranian_languages), [Old Azeri](/Old_Azeri), which was gradually supplanted by a [Turkic language](/Turkic_languages), the ancestor of modern [Azerbaijani language](/Azerbaijani_language). [57] Some linguists propose that the [Tati dialects](/Tat_language_(Caucasus)) spoken in [Iranian Azerbaijan](/Azerbaijan_(Iran)) and the Republic of Azerbaijan, like those of the [Tats](/Tat_people_(Caucasus)), are descendants of Old Azeri. [58] [59]

Locally, the territories of the subsequent Seljuk Empire were governed by the [Eldiguzids](/Eldiguzids). While technically vassals of the Seljuk sultans, they often acted as de facto rulers. Under Seljuk influence, local poets such as [Nizami Ganjavi](/Nizami_Ganjavi) and [Khaqani](/Khaqani) contributed to a flourishing of [Persian literature](/Persian_literature) in the region. [60] [61]

The [Shirvanshahs](/Shirvanshahs), a local dynasty of Arabic origin that later became Persianized, served as a vassal state to the [Timurid Empire](/Timurid_Empire) of [Timur](/Timur). They assisted Timur in his conflict against [Tokhtamysh](/Tokhtamysh), the ruler of the [Golden Horde](/Golden_Horde). Following Timur's demise, two independent and competing Turkoman states emerged: [Qara Qoyunlu](/Qara_Qoyunlu) and [Aq Qoyunlu](/Aq_Qoyunlu). The Shirvanshahs reasserted their influence, maintaining a significant degree of autonomy as local rulers and vassals since 861. In 1501, the [Safavid dynasty](/Safavid_dynasty) of Iran subjugated the Shirvanshahs and acquired their territories. Over the next century, the Safavids [converted the predominantly Sunni population to Shia Islam](/Safavid_conversion_of_Iran_to_Shia_Islam), [62] [63] [64] mirroring their actions in what is now Iran. [65] The Safavids permitted the Shirvanshahs to retain power under Safavid suzerainty until 1538, when Safavid King [Tahmasp I](/Tahmasp_I) deposed them, establishing the area as the Safavid [province of Shirvan](/Safavid_Shirvan). The Sunni Ottomans briefly occupied parts of present-day Azerbaijan as a result of the [Ottoman–Safavid War of 1578–1590](/Ottoman%E2%80%93Safavid_War_(1578%E2%80%931590)). By the early 17th century, they were expelled by the Safavid ruler [Abbas I](/Abbas_I_of_Persia). In the aftermath of the Safavid dynasty's decline, [Baku](/Baku) and its surrounding areas experienced a brief Russian occupation following the [Russo-Persian War of 1722–1723](/Russo-Persian_War_(1722%E2%80%931723)). The remaining territories of present-day Azerbaijan were [occupied by the Ottomans](/Nader_Shah) between 1722 and 1736. [66] Despite these intermittent occupations by Safavid Iran's rivals, the territory remained under Iranian rule from the early Safavid period until the 19th century. [67] [68]

##### Modern history

A political map of the eastern part of the [South Caucasus](/South_Caucasus) between 1795 and 1801.

Following the Safavids, the region came under the rule of the Iranian [Afsharid dynasty](/Afsharid_dynasty). After [Nader Shah](/Nader_Shah)'s assassination in 1747, many of his former subjects capitalized on the ensuing instability. Numerous [khanates](/Khanates_of_the_Caucasus), possessing varying degrees of autonomy, [69] [70] [71] [72] [73] [74] emerged. The rulers of these khanates were often closely related to ruling dynasties in Iran and served as vassals and [subjects](/Commoners) to the Iranian shah. [74] These khanates exerted control over their internal affairs and engaged in international trade along routes connecting Central Asia and the West. [75]

Subsequently, the area fell under the successive rule of the Iranian [Zands](/Zand_dynasty) and [Qajars](/Qajar_dynasty). [76] From the late 18th century, [Imperial Russia](/Russian_Empire) adopted a more aggressive geopolitical stance towards Iran and the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire). [77] Russia actively sought to acquire the Caucasus region, which was largely controlled by Iran. [78] In 1804, Russian forces [invaded and sacked the Iranian town of Ganja](/Siege_of_Ganja_(1804)), triggering the [Russo-Persian War of 1804–1813](/Russo-Persian_War_(1804%E2%80%9313)). [79] The militarily superior Russians ultimately won the war. [80] Following Qajar Iran's defeat, it was compelled to cede sovereignty over most of the khanates, along with Georgia and Dagestan, to the Russian Empire through the [Treaty of Gulistan](/Treaty_of_Gulistan). [81]

[The siege of Ganja Fortress in 1804](/Battle_of_Ganja_(1804)) during the Russo-Persian War of 1804–1813.

The region north of the Aras River was Iranian territory until its occupation by Russia in the 19th century. [14] [82] [83] [84] [85] [86] [87] Approximately a decade later, in contravention of the Gulistan treaty, Russian forces invaded Iran's [Erivan Khanate](/Erivan_Khanate). [87] [88] This act initiated the final period of hostilities between the two powers, the [Russo-Persian War of 1826–1828](/Russo-Persian_War_(1826-1828)). The ensuing [Treaty of Turkmenchay](/Treaty_of_Turkmenchay) forced Qajar Iran to relinquish sovereignty over the Erivan Khanate, the [Nakhchivan Khanate](/Nakhchivan_Khanate), and the remaining parts of the [Talysh Khanate](/Talysh_Khanate). [81] With the incorporation of all Caucasian territories from Iran into Russia, the border between the two nations was established along the Aras River. [89]

Despite the Russian conquest, throughout the 19th century, a strong connection to [Iranian culture](/Culture_of_Iran), [literature](/Literature_of_Iran), and language persisted among Shia and Sunni intellectuals in Russian-held cities like Baku, Ganja, and Tiflis (now [Tbilisi](/Tbilisi), Georgia). [90] Within this same period, in Russian-controlled East Caucasia, an Azerbaijani national identity began to emerge towards the end of the 19th century. [91] As a consequence of the Russian conquest, Azerbaijanis are now divided between two nations: Iran and Azerbaijan. [92]

Following the collapse of the Russian Empire during [World War I](/World_War_I), the short-lived [Transcaucasian Democratic Federative Republic](/Transcaucasian_Democratic_Federative_Republic) was proclaimed, encompassing the present-day republics of Azerbaijan, Georgia, and Armenia. This period was marked by the [March Days](/March_Days) massacres, which occurred between March 30 and April 2, 1918, in Baku and adjacent areas of the [Baku Governorate]. [93] [94] [95] Upon the republic's dissolution in May 1918, the dominant [Musavat](/Musavat) party declared independence as the [Azerbaijan Democratic Republic](/Azerbaijan_Democratic_Republic) (ADR). This declaration adopted the name "Azerbaijan," a designation that, prior to the ADR's proclamation, had been exclusively applied to the adjacent [northwestern region of contemporary Iran](/Iranian_Azerbaijan). [38] [39] [40] The ADR represented the first modern [parliamentary republic](/Parliamentary_republic) within the Muslim world. [14] [96] [97] A significant achievement of the Parliament was the extension of suffrage to women, making the ADR the first Muslim nation to grant women equal political rights. [96] [Baku State University](/Baku_State_University), the first modern university established in the Muslim East, was founded during this era. [96]

A map presented by the Azerbaijani delegation at the [1919 Paris Peace Conference](/Paris_Peace_Conference,_1919).

Independent Azerbaijan's existence was brief, lasting only 23 months until the [Bolshevik](/Bolshevik) [11th Soviet Red Army](/11th_Army_(RSFSR)) invaded, establishing the [Azerbaijan Soviet Socialist Republic](/Azerbaijan_Soviet_Socialist_Republic) on 28 April 1920. Despite the majority of the newly formed Azerbaijani army being engaged in suppressing an Armenian uprising in [Karabakh](/Karabakh), Azerbaijanis did not relinquish their brief independence of 1918–20 easily. An estimated 20,000 Azerbaijani soldiers perished resisting what amounted to a Russian reconquest. [98] During the initial Soviet period, the Azerbaijani national identity was further solidified. [91]

On 13 October 1921, the Soviet republics of Russia, Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Georgia signed the [Treaty of Kars] with Turkey. The previously independent [Republic of Aras](/Republic_of_Aras) subsequently became the [Nakhchivan Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic](/Nakhchivan_Autonomous_Soviet_Socialist_Republic) within the Azerbaijan SSR, as stipulated by the Treaty of Kars. [14] [99] Conversely, Armenia was granted the region of [Zangezur](/Syunik_Province), and Turkey agreed to return [Gyumri](/Gyumri) (then known as Alexandropol). [100]

During [World War II](/World_War_II), Azerbaijan played a critical role in the Soviet Union's strategic energy policy, supplying 80% of the oil used on the [Eastern Front](/Eastern_Front_(World_War_II)) from Baku. By decree of the [Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union](/Supreme_Soviet_of_the_Soviet_Union) in February 1942, the contributions of over 500 oil industry workers and employees from Azerbaijan were recognized with orders and medals. [Operation Edelweiss], carried out by the German [Wehrmacht](/Wehrmacht), specifically targeted Baku due to its vital importance as the USSR's energy hub. [14] Approximately one-fifth of all Azerbaijanis served in World War II, from 1941 to 1945. An estimated 681,000 individuals (including over 100,000 women) were deployed to the front lines, out of a total Azerbaijani population of 3.4 million at the time. [101] Around 250,000 Azerbaijanis were killed in the war. More than 130 Azerbaijanis were awarded the title of [Hero of the Soviet Union](/Hero_of_the_Soviet_Union), with Major-General [Azi Aslanov](/Azi_Aslanov) receiving this honor twice. [102]

##### Independence

[Soviet Army](/Soviet_Army) [paratroopers](/Paratrooper) during the [Black January](/Black_January) tragedy in 1990.

Following the policies of [glasnost](/Glasnost) introduced by [Mikhail Gorbachev](/Mikhail_Gorbachev), civil unrest and ethnic tensions escalated across various Soviet republics, including [Nagorno-Karabakh](/Nagorno-Karabakh_Autonomous_Oblast), an autonomous region within the Azerbaijan SSR. [103] The disturbances in Azerbaijan, fueled by Moscow's perceived indifference to the escalating conflict, led to widespread calls for independence and secession. These sentiments culminated in the [Black January](/Black_January) events in Baku. [104] Later in 1990, the [Supreme Council of the Azerbaijan SSR](/Supreme_Soviet_of_Azerbaijan_SSR) removed the words "Soviet Socialist" from the country's official title, adopted the "Declaration of Sovereignty of the Azerbaijan Republic," and reinstated the flag of the Azerbaijan Democratic Republic as the state flag. [105] In the wake of the failed [1991 Soviet coup attempt](/1991_Soviet_coup_attempt) in Moscow, the Supreme Council of Azerbaijan passed a Declaration of Independence on 18 October 1991, which was subsequently confirmed by a nationwide referendum in December, coinciding with the official dissolution of the Soviet Union on 26 December. [105] The country commemorates its [Day of Restoration of Independence](/Day_of_Restoration_of_Independence_(Azerbaijan)) on 18 October. [106]

The early years of independence were heavily overshadowed by the [First Nagorno-Karabakh War], fought against the ethnic Armenian majority of Nagorno-Karabakh, supported by Armenia. [107] By the conclusion of hostilities in 1994, Armenian forces controlled approximately 14–16% of Azerbaijani territory, including Nagorno-Karabakh. [26] [108] The war was marked by numerous atrocities and pogroms perpetrated by both sides, including the massacres at [Malibeyli, Gushchular](/Capture_of_Gushchular_and_Malibeyli) and [Garadaghly](/Capture_of_Garadaghly), the [Khojaly massacre](/Khojaly_massacre), as well as the [Baku pogrom](/Baku_pogrom), the [Maraga massacre](/Maraga_massacre), and the [Kirovabad pogrom]. [109] [110] Furthermore, an estimated 30,000 people were killed, and over a million people were displaced (more than 800,000 Azerbaijanis and 300,000 Armenians). [111] Four [United Nations Security Council](/United_Nations_Security_Council) resolutions ([822](/United_Nations_Security_Council_Resolution_822), [853](/United_Nations_Security_Council_Resolution_853), [874](/United_Nations_Security_Council_Resolution_874), and [884](/United_Nations_Security_Council_Resolution_884)) explicitly demanded "the immediate withdrawal of all Armenian forces from all occupied territories of Azerbaijan." [112] Many Russians and Armenians fled Azerbaijan as refugees during the 1990s. [113] According to the 1970 census, Azerbaijan was home to 510,000 ethnic [Russians](/Russian_diaspora) and 484,000 Armenians. [114]

##### Aliyev family rule, 1993–present

The military situation in the Nagorno-Karabakh region prior to the [Second Nagorno-Karabakh War](/Second_Nagorno-Karabakh_War).

In 1993, democratically elected President [Abulfaz Elchibey](/Abulfaz_Elchibey) was overthrown by a military insurrection led by Colonel [Surat Huseynov](/Surat_Huseynov), which paved the way for the ascent of the former leader of Soviet Azerbaijan, [Heydar Aliyev](/Heydar_Aliyev). In 1994, Huseynov, by then the prime minister, attempted another military coup against Heydar Aliyev but was arrested and charged with treason. [115] In 1995, yet another coup attempt was made against Aliyev, this time by [Rovshan Javadov](/Rovshan_Javadov), the commander of the Russian [OMON](/OMON) special police unit. The coup was thwarted, resulting in Javadov's death and the disbandment of Azerbaijan's OMON units. [116] [117] Concurrently, the country was plagued by pervasive corruption within its governing bureaucracy. [118] In October 1998, Aliyev secured re-election for a second term.

[Ilham Aliyev](/Ilham_Aliyev), Heydar Aliyev's son, assumed the chairmanship of the [New Azerbaijan Party](/New_Azerbaijan_Party) and the presidency of Azerbaijan upon his father's death in 2003. He was re-elected for a third term as president in October 2013. [119] In April 2018, Aliyev secured his fourth consecutive term in an election boycotted by the main opposition parties due to allegations of fraud. [120] On 27 September 2020, hostilities reignited along the [Nagorno-Karabakh Line of Contact] in the ongoing [Nagorno-Karabakh conflict]. Both Azerbaijani and Armenian armed forces reported military and civilian casualties. [121] The [Nagorno-Karabakh ceasefire agreement] and the cessation of the six-week [war between Azerbaijan and Armenia](/Second_Nagorno-Karabakh_War) were met with widespread celebration in Azerbaijan, as the country achieved significant territorial gains. [122] Despite an improving economy, [123] particularly through the exploitation of the [Azeri–Chirag–Guneshli](/Azeri%E2%80%93Chirag%E2%80%93Gunashli) oil field and the [Shah Deniz gas field](/Shah_Deniz_gas_field), the Aliyev family's rule has faced criticism for alleged election fraud, [124] significant economic inequality, [125] and domestic corruption. [126] In September 2023, Azerbaijan launched an offensive against the breakaway [Republic of Artsakh](/Republic_of_Artsakh) in Nagorno-Karabakh, leading to its dissolution and reintegration into Azerbaijan on 1 January 2024, and the subsequent [flight of nearly all ethnic Armenians from the region]. [127] [128] [129]

On 8 August 2025, Azerbaijani President [Ilham Aliyev](/Ilham_Aliyev) and Armenian Prime Minister [Nikol Pashinyan](/Nikol_Pashinyan) signed a joint declaration at the [White House](/White_House), [130] formalizing a [peace deal](/Armenia%E2%80%93Azerbaijan_peace_agreement) facilitated by the [Trump administration](/Second_presidency_of_Donald_Trump), aiming to end nearly four decades of conflict between the two nations. [131]

### Geography

• Main articles: [Geography of Azerbaijan](/Geography_of_Azerbaijan), [State reserves of Azerbaijan](/State_reserves_of_Azerbaijan), and [National parks of Azerbaijan](/National_parks_of_Azerbaijan)
• See also: [Extreme points of Azerbaijan](/Extreme_points_of_Azerbaijan)

A map illustrating the [Köppen-Geiger climate classification](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification) for Azerbaijan. [132]

Azerbaijan is situated in the [South Caucasus](/South_Caucasus) region of [Eurasia](/Eurasia), straddling the geographical divide between [West Asia](/West_Asia) and [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe). Its latitudinal extent is between 38° and 42° N, and its longitudinal position is between 44° and 51° E. The total length of its land borders is 2,648 km (1,645 mi). These borders are shared with Armenia (1,007 km / 626 mi), Iran (756 km / 470 mi), Georgia (480 km), Russia (390 km / 242 mi), and Turkey (15 km / 9 mi). [133] The Caspian Sea coastline stretches for 800 km (497 mi), with the widest section of the Azerbaijani Caspian coast measuring 456 km (283 mi). [133] The country possesses a landlocked [exclave](/Enclave_and_exclave), the [Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic](/Nakhchivan_Autonomous_Republic). [134]

The [Caucasus Mountains](/Caucasus_Mountains) form a prominent feature in northern Azerbaijan.

Three dominant geographical features define Azerbaijan: the Caspian Sea, whose shoreline forms the eastern boundary; the [Greater Caucasus](/Greater_Caucasus) mountain range to the north; and the extensive plains in the country's center. Mountain ranges, including the Greater and [Lesser Caucasus](/Lesser_Caucasus) and the [Talysh Mountains](/Talysh_Mountains), cover approximately 40% of the nation's territory. [135] The highest point is [Mount Bazardüzü](/Mount_Bazard%C3%BCz%C3%BC), reaching an elevation of 4,466 m (14,652 ft). The lowest point is situated in the Caspian Sea, at -28 m (-92 ft). Azerbaijan hosts nearly half of the world's [mud volcanoes](/Mud_volcano), with these geological formations [Mud_volcanoes_in_Azerbaijan] being among the nominees for the [New 7 Wonders of Nature](/New_7_Wonders_of_Nature). [136]

Surface waters constitute the primary water sources. Out of the 8,350 streams, only 24 exceed 100 km (62 mi) in length. [135] All streams ultimately drain into the Caspian Sea. [135] The largest lake is [Sarysu](/Lake_Sarysu), covering 67 km² (26 sq mi). The longest river is the [Kura](/Kura_(Caspian_Sea)), which flows for 1,515 km (941 mi) and is [transboundary](/Transboundary_river), shared with Armenia. Azerbaijan also has numerous islands along the Caspian Sea coast, largely concentrated within the [Baku Archipelago](/Baku_Archipelago).

Since gaining independence in 1991, the government has implemented measures to preserve Azerbaijan's [environment](/Environment_of_Azerbaijan). Environmental protection efforts intensified after 2001, bolstered by increased state revenues from the [Baku–Tbilisi–Ceyhan pipeline](/Baku%E2%80%93Tbilisi%E2%80%93Ceyhan_pipeline). Within four years, protected areas doubled, now encompassing 8% of the country's territory. Since 2001, the government has established seven major reserves and nearly doubled the budget allocated to environmental protection. [137]

#### Landscape

• Main articles: [Orography of Azerbaijan](/Orography_of_Azerbaijan), [Climate of Azerbaijan](/Climate_of_Azerbaijan), and [Water bodies of Azerbaijan](/Water_bodies_of_Azerbaijan)

[Mount Bazarduzu](/Mount_Bazard%C3%BCz%C3%BC), Azerbaijan's highest peak, as viewed from [Mount Shahdagh](/Mount_Shahdagh).
The landscape of the Khinalug valley.

Azerbaijan presents a diverse range of landscapes. Over half of its landmass consists of mountain ridges, crests, highlands, and plateaus, rising to elevations of 400–1,000 meters (including mid- and lower-level lowlands). In certain areas, such as the Talysh, Jeyranchol-Ajinohur, and Langabiz-Alat foothills, elevations reach 100–120 meters, while others, like Qobustan and Absheron, range from 0–50 meters. [138] [139] The remaining terrain comprises plains and lowlands. Elevations within the Caucasus region vary from approximately -28 meters at the Caspian Sea shoreline to 4,466 meters at the [Bazardüzü](/Mount_Bazard%C3%BCz%C3%BC) peak. [138] [139]

The country's climate is influenced by cold arctic [air masses](/Air_mass) originating from the Scandinavian [anticyclone], temperate air masses from the [Siberian](/Siberia) anticyclone, and the Central Asian anticyclone. [140] [141] [142] Azerbaijan's topography significantly affects how these air masses enter the country. [140] The Greater Caucasus range provides a natural barrier, shielding the country from the direct impact of cold northern air masses. This protection fosters the development of a [subtropical climate](/Subtropics) across most foothills and plains. [143] [144]

Azerbaijan encompasses nine of the eleven existing [climate zones](/K%C3%B6ppen_climate_classification). [145] The extreme recorded temperatures, both minimum (-33 °C or -27.4 °F) and maximum, were observed in the [Julfa](/Julfa_District) and [Ordubad](/Ordubad_District) regions of the [Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic](/Nakhchivan_Autonomous_Republic). [145] The highest annual precipitation occurs in [Lankaran], ranging from 1,600 to 1,800 mm (63 to 71 in), while the lowest precipitation is recorded in Absheron, between 200 and 350 mm (7.9 to 13.8 in). [145] [146] [147]

[Murovdag](/Murovdag) stands as the highest [mountain range](/Mountain_range) within the [Lesser Caucasus](/Lesser_Caucasus).

Rivers and lakes form the principal components of Azerbaijan's water systems, shaped over extensive geological periods and subject to continuous evolution. Evidence of ancient river systems is found throughout the country. These water systems are constantly altered by natural forces and human industrial activities. Canals and ponds are integrated into Azerbaijan's water infrastructure. In terms of water supply, Azerbaijan falls below the global average, with approximately 100,000 cubic meters (3,531,467 cubic feet) of water available per square kilometer annually. [145] The major [water reservoirs](/Reservoir) are situated on the Kura River. Azerbaijan's hydrography is part of the Caspian Sea basin.

The [Kura](/Kura_(South_Caucasus_river)) and [Aras](/Aras_(river)) are the principal rivers in Azerbaijan, flowing through the [Kura-Aras lowland](/Kura-Aras_lowland). Rivers that flow directly into the Caspian Sea originate primarily from the northeastern slopes of the Major Caucasus and Talysh Mountains, traversing the Samur–Devechi and Lankaran lowlands. [148] [149]

[Yanar Dag](/Yanar_Dagh), translating to "burning mountain," is a natural gas fire that perpetually blazes on a hillside on the [Absheron Peninsula](/Absheron_Peninsula), near Baku. The peninsula itself is known as the "land of fire." Flames erupt from a porous sandstone layer, making it a notable tourist attraction for visitors to the Baku region. [150]

#### Biodiversity

• Main article: [Wildlife of Azerbaijan](/Wildlife_of_Azerbaijan)
• Further information: [Fauna of Azerbaijan](/Fauna_of_Azerbaijan) and [Flora of Azerbaijan](/Flora_of_Azerbaijan)

The [Karabakh horse](/Karabakh_horse) is recognized as the national animal of Azerbaijan.

Early accounts of Azerbaijan's rich and diverse animal life can be found in the travelogues of Eastern travelers. Animal depictions carved into architectural monuments, ancient rocks, and stones have survived to the present day. Initial documentation of Azerbaijan's flora and fauna was gathered by naturalists who visited the region in the 17th century. [135]

A total of 106 mammal species, 97 fish species, 363 bird species, 10 amphibian species, and 52 reptile species have been recorded and classified in Azerbaijan. [135] The national animal of Azerbaijan is the [Karabakh horse](/Karabakh_horse), a breed endemic to the region, known for mountain-steppe racing and riding. The Karabakh horse is renowned for its good temperament, speed, elegance, and intelligence. It is one of the oldest horse breeds, with ancestry tracing back to antiquity, though it is now considered an endangered species. [151]

Azerbaijan's flora comprises over 4,500 species of higher plants. Due to its unique climate, the flora is considerably richer in species diversity compared to other South Caucasus republics, with 66% of plant species found in the entire [Caucasus](/Caucasus) present in Azerbaijan. [152] The country falls within four ecoregions: [Caspian Hyrcanian mixed forests](/Caspian_Hyrcanian_mixed_forests), [Caucasus mixed forests](/Caucasus_mixed_forests), [Eastern Anatolian montane steppe](/Eastern_Anatolian_montane_steppe), and [Azerbaijan shrub desert and steppe](/Azerbaijan_shrub_desert_and_steppe). [153]

In 2018, Azerbaijan recorded a mean score of 6.55 out of 10 for the [Forest Landscape Integrity Index](/Forest_Landscape_Integrity_Index), ranking 72nd globally among 172 countries. [154] Forest cover constitutes approximately 14% of the total land area, equivalent to 1,131,770 hectares (ha) in 2020, an increase from 944,740 hectares (ha) in 1990. In 2020, naturally regenerating forests covered 826,200 hectares (ha), with planted forests accounting for 305,570 hectares (ha). Of the naturally regenerating forest area, 0% was classified as [primary forest](/Primary_forest) (defined as native tree species without clear signs of human activity), and approximately 33% of the forest area was located within protected zones. In 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under [public ownership](/State_ownership), with 0% under [private ownership](/Private_property) and 0% with ownership categorized as other or unknown. [155] [156]

### Government and politics

• Main article: [Politics of Azerbaijan](/Politics_of_Azerbaijan)
• See also: [Elections in Azerbaijan](/Elections_in_Azerbaijan) and [Human rights in Azerbaijan](/Human_rights_in_Azerbaijan)

[Ilham Aliyev](/Ilham_Aliyev), President of Azerbaijan.
[Mehriban Aliyeva](/Mehriban_Aliyeva), Vice President of Azerbaijan.
[Ali Asadov](/Ali_Asadov), Prime Minister of Azerbaijan.

A government building in Baku.

Azerbaijan's governance operates in practice as an authoritarian regime. [157] [158] [159] [160] Although regular [elections](/Elections_in_Azerbaijan) are held, they are reportedly marred by [electoral fraud](/Electoral_fraud) and other unfair electoral practices. [161] [162] [163] [164] [165] [166] [167] The government has been continuously led by the [Aliyev political family](/Political_family) and the [New Azerbaijan Party](/New_Azerbaijan_Party) (Yeni Azərbaycan Partiyası, YAP), established by [Heydar Aliyev](/Heydar_Aliyev), since 1993. [168] [Freedom House](/Freedom_House) categorizes Azerbaijan as "not free," ranking it 7/100 on its Global Freedom Score in 2024 and describing its regime as authoritarian. [169] [170] [171]

The framework of the political system was finalized with the adoption of the [constitution](/Constitution_of_Azerbaijan) on 12 November 1995. According to Article 23 of the constitution, the [state symbols](/National_symbol) include the [flag](/Flag_of_Azerbaijan), the [coat of arms](/Coat_of_arms_of_Azerbaijan), and the [national anthem](/National_Anthem_of_the_Republic_of_Azerbaijan). State power is limited by law concerning internal matters; however, international affairs are also constrained by the provisions of international agreements. [172] [better source needed](/Wikipedia:NOTRS)

The Constitution of Azerbaijan establishes it as a presidential republic with three distinct branches of power: executive, legislative, and judicial. Legislative authority is vested in the [unicameral](/Unicameralism) [National Assembly](/National_Assembly_of_Azerbaijan) and the Supreme National Assembly within the Nakhchivan Autonomous Republic. The [Parliament of Azerbaijan](/National_Assembly_(Azerbaijan)), known as the Milli Majlis, comprises 125 deputies elected through [majority vote](/First-past-the-post_voting), serving five-year terms. Elections are conducted every five years on the first Sunday of November. While the Parliament does not form the government, the constitution mandates the approval of the Cabinet of Ministers by the Milli Majlis. [173] The New Azerbaijan Party and independents aligned with the ruling government currently hold nearly all of the Parliament's 125 seats. During the [2010 Parliamentary election](/2010_Azerbaijani_parliamentary_election), opposition parties, [Musavat](/Musavat) and the [Azerbaijani Popular Front Party](/Azerbaijani_Popular_Front_Party), failed to secure any seats. European observers noted numerous irregularities during the election campaign and on election day. [174]

Executive power is exercised by the [president](/President_of_Azerbaijan), who is elected for a seven-year term via direct popular vote, and the [prime minister](/Prime_Minister_of_Azerbaijan). The president holds the authority to establish the [Cabinet](/Cabinet_of_Azerbaijan), a collective executive body accountable to both the president and the National Assembly. [4] The Cabinet is composed primarily of the prime minister, his deputies, and ministers. The [8th Government of Azerbaijan](/8th_Government_of_Azerbaijan) represents the current administration. While the president cannot dissolve the National Assembly, he possesses the power to veto its decisions. To override a presidential veto, the parliament requires a majority of 95 votes. Judicial power resides within the [Constitutional Court](/Constitutional_Court_of_Azerbaijan), the [Supreme Court](/Supreme_Court_of_Azerbaijan), and the Economic Court. The president nominates the judges for these courts. [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)

Azerbaijan's governance structure can be described as nominally two-tiered. The highest tier of government is the executive power, headed by the president. Local executive authorities function as extensions of this central executive power. The legal framework for local executive administration (Yerli Icra Hakimiyati) was established by a regulation adopted on 16 June 1999. In June 2012, the president approved a regulation that granted enhanced powers to local executive authorities, thereby strengthening their influence in local governance. [175] The Security Council, established on 10 April 1997, serves as a deliberative body under the president, organized according to constitutional provisions. The administrative department, distinct from the president's office, oversees the financial, technical, and budgetary activities of both the president and his office. [176]

### Foreign relations

• Main article: [Foreign relations of Azerbaijan](/Foreign_relations_of_Azerbaijan)
• See also: [Azerbaijan and the European Union](/Azerbaijan_and_the_European_Union)

President [İlham Aliyev](/%C4%B0lham_Aliyev) accepting the Supreme Order of the Turkic World from Turkish President [Recep Tayyip Erdoğan](/Recep_Tayyip_Erdo%C4%9Fan) during the 8th summit of the [Organization of Turkic States](/Organization_of_Turkic_States) in [Istanbul](/Istanbul), Turkey, on 12 November 2021.

The brief existence of the Azerbaijan Democratic Republic saw the establishment of diplomatic relations with six countries, including diplomatic representation in Germany and Finland. [177] The process of international recognition of Azerbaijan's independence from the disintegrating Soviet Union spanned approximately one year. Bahrain was the most recent country to recognize Azerbaijan, on 6 November 1996. [178] Full diplomatic relations, including mutual establishment of missions, were first instituted with Turkey, Pakistan, the United States, Iran, [177] and Israel. [179] Azerbaijan places particular emphasis on its "special relationship" with Turkey. [180] [181]

To date, Azerbaijan maintains diplomatic relations with 158 countries and is a member of 38 international organizations. [23] It holds observer status in the [Non-Aligned Movement](/Non-Aligned_Movement) and the [World Trade Organization](/World_Trade_Organization), and is a correspondent member of the [International Telecommunication Union](/International_Telecommunication_Union). [23] On 9 May 2006, Azerbaijan was elected to membership in the newly established [Human Rights Council](/Human_Rights_Council) by the [United Nations General Assembly](/United_Nations_General_Assembly), commencing its term on 19 June 2006. Azerbaijan secured its first non-permanent seat on the [UN Security Council in 2011](/United_Nations_Security_Council_election,_2011) with the support of 155 countries.

President [Ilham Aliyev](/Ilham_Aliyev) and other heads of state are hosted by Kazakh President [Nursultan Nazarbayev](/Nursultan_Nazarbayev) at the [Caspian Summit](/Caspian_Summit) in [Aktau](/Aktau), Kazakhstan, on 12 August 2018.

Foreign policy priorities are primarily focused on restoring territorial integrity, addressing the consequences of the occupation of Nagorno-Karabakh and the seven surrounding regions, [183] [184] integration into European and Euro-Atlantic structures, contributing to international security, cooperating with international organizations, fostering regional cooperation and bilateral relations, strengthening defense capabilities, promoting security through domestic policy measures, reinforcing democracy, maintaining ethnic and religious tolerance, advancing scientific, educational, and cultural policies, preserving moral values, ensuring economic and social development, enhancing internal and border security, and addressing migration, energy, and transportation security. [183]

Azerbaijan actively participates in international coalitions combating terrorism and was among the first nations to offer support following the [September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks). [185] The country is an active member of [NATO](/NATO)'s [Partnership for Peace](/Partnership_for_Peace) program, contributing to peacekeeping operations in Kosovo, Afghanistan, and Iraq. [citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) Azerbaijan has been a [member](/Member_states_of_the_Council_of_Europe) of the [Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe) since 2001 and maintains positive relations with the European Union, with potential future application for EU membership being a possibility. [183]

President Ilham Aliyev, US President [Donald Trump](/Donald_Trump), and Armenian Prime Minister [Nikol Pashinyan](/Nikol_Pashinyan) signing a trilateral [joint declaration](/Armenia%E2%80%93Azerbaijan_peace_agreement) in Washington, D.C., on 8 August 2025.

On 1 July 2021, the US Congress advanced legislation impacting military aid allocated to Azerbaijan since 2012, with a notable shift in focus towards Armenia. [186]

Azerbaijan has faced significant criticism for allegedly bribing foreign officials and diplomats to advance its agenda abroad and legitimize its domestic elections, a practice referred to as [caviar diplomacy]. [187] [188] [189] [190] The [Azerbaijani laundromat](/Azerbaijani_laundromat) money laundering scheme involved bribing foreign politicians and journalists to serve the Azerbaijani government's public relations interests. [191]

### Military

• Main article: [Azerbaijani Armed Forces](/Azerbaijani_Armed_Forces)

[Azerbaijani Navy](/Azerbaijani_Navy) vessels during the 2022 Teknofest Azerbaijan festival in [Baku](/Baku).

The National Army of the Azerbaijan Democratic Republic was established on 26 June 1918. [192] [193] Upon gaining independence following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, the Armed Forces of the Republic of Azerbaijan were constituted in accordance with the law on armed forces dated 9 October 1991. [194] The anniversary of the establishment of the short-lived National Army is observed as Army Day on 26 June. [195] As of 2021, Azerbaijan maintained 126,000 active personnel in its armed forces, supplemented by 17,000 paramilitary troops and 330,000 reservists. [196] The armed forces comprise three branches: the [Land Forces](/Army_of_Azerbaijan), the [Air Forces](/Azerbaijani_Air_Forces), and the [Navy](/Azerbaijan_Navy). Additionally, the armed forces encompass several paramilitary sub-groups that can be mobilized for national defense, including the [Internal Troops](/Internal_Troops_of_Azerbaijan) of the Ministry of Internal Affairs and the [State Border Service](/State_Border_Service_of_Azerbaijan), which includes the Coast Guard. [26] The [Azerbaijani National Guard](/Azerbaijani_National_Guard) operates as a semi-independent force under the Special State Protection Service, an agency subordinate to the president. [197]

Members of the [Special Forces of Azerbaijan](/Special_Forces_of_Azerbaijan) during the [Baku Victory Parade of 2020](/Baku_Victory_Parade_of_2020).

Azerbaijan adheres to the [Treaty on Conventional Armed Forces in Europe](/Treaty_on_Conventional_Armed_Forces_in_Europe) and has ratified all major international arms and weapons treaties. Azerbaijan collaborates closely with [NATO](/NATO) within programs such as [Partnership for Peace](/Partnership_for_Peace) and the [Individual Partnership Action Plan/pfp and ipa](/Individual_Partnership_Action_Plan). Azerbaijan has deployed 151 peacekeeping forces to Iraq and an additional 184 to Afghanistan. [198]

As of 2020, Azerbaijan's defense budget amounted to $2.24 billion, [update] representing 5.4% of its total GDP [200] and approximately 12.7% of general government expenditure. [201] The Azerbaijani [defense industry](/Ministry_of_Defence_Industry_of_Azerbaijan) is capable of manufacturing small arms, artillery systems, tanks, armored vehicles, [night vision devices](/Night_vision_device), aviation bombs, UAVs (unmanned aerial vehicles), various military vehicles, and military aircraft and helicopters. [202] [203] [204] [205]

### Human rights and freedom

• Main article: [Human rights in Azerbaijan](/Human_rights_in_Azerbaijan)

Human rights activist [Rufat Safarov](/Rufat_Safarov), arrested on December 4, 2024.

While the constitution guarantees freedom of speech, this right is not upheld in practice. Following several years of decline in press and media freedom, the media environment deteriorated significantly in 2014 amid a government campaign to silence opposition and criticism, even as the country presided over the Committee of Ministers of the [Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe) (May–November 2014). The use of spurious legal charges and impunity for violence against journalists has become commonplace. [206] All foreign broadcasts are prohibited within the country. [207] According to the 2013 [Freedom House](/Freedom_House) Freedom of the Press report, Azerbaijan's press freedom status is rated as "not free," with the country ranking 177th out of 196 nations. [208] As of 2025, there were 375 political prisoners in Azerbaijan. [209] [Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty](/Radio_Free_Europe/Radio_Liberty) and [Voice of America](/Voice_of_America) are banned in Azerbaijan. [210] Discrimination against [LGBT people](/LGBT_rights_in_Azerbaijan) is widespread in the country. [211] [212]

Christianity is officially recognized. All religious communities are required to register to be permitted to gather, facing potential imprisonment if they fail to comply. This registration process is frequently denied. [213] [214]

Azerbaijani journalist [Khayala Aghayeva](/Khayala_Aghayeva) was apprehended in December 2024 in connection with a criminal case initiated against [Meydan TV](/Meydan_TV) journalists.

In 2015, Azerbaijan had the highest number of imprisoned journalists in Europe, according to the [Committee to Protect Journalists](/Committee_to_Protect_Journalists), and is ranked as the 5th most censored country globally, surpassing Iran and China. [215] Some critical journalists have faced arrest for their reporting on the [COVID-19 pandemic in Azerbaijan](/COVID-19_pandemic_in_Azerbaijan). [216] [217] Journalists from independent outlets such as [Abzas Media](/Abzas_Media), Toplum TV, and [Meydan TV](/Meydan_TV) were prosecuted in 2024 and 2025 in trials that international human rights organizations deemed unfair. [218] [219] [220]

An October 2015 report by an [Amnesty International](/Amnesty_International) researcher highlighted "...the severe deterioration of human rights in Azerbaijan over the past few years. Sadly Azerbaijan has been allowed to get away with unprecedented levels of repression and in the process almost wipe out its civil society." [221] Amnesty's 2015/16 annual report [222] concerning the country stated that "...persecution of political dissent continued. Human rights organizations remained unable to resume their work. At least 18 prisoners of conscience remained in detention at the end of the year. Reprisals against independent journalists and activists persisted both within the country and abroad, while their family members also faced harassment and arrests. International human rights monitors were barred and expelled from the country. Reports of torture and other ill-treatment persisted." [223]

[The Guardian](/The_Guardian) reported in April 2017 that "Azerbaijan's ruling elite operated a secret $2.9bn (£2.2bn) scheme to pay prominent Europeans, buy luxury goods and launder money through a network of opaque British companies .... Leaked data shows that the Azerbaijani leadership, accused of serial human rights abuses, systemic corruption and rigging elections, made more than 16,000 covert payments from 2012 to 2014. Some of this money went to politicians and journalists, as part of an international lobbying operation to deflect criticism of Azerbaijan's president, Ilham Aliyev, and to promote a positive image of his oil-rich country." It was noted that there was no suggestion that all recipients were aware of the money's origin due to its disguised route. [224]

