#### Languages

• Main article: [Languages of Azerbaijan](/Languages_of_Azerbaijan)

The official language is [Azerbaijani](/Azerbaijani_language), a [Turkic language](/Turkic_languages). Approximately 96% of the national population speaks it as their [mother tongue](/Mother_tongue). Russian is still spoken in Azerbaijan, serving as the mother tongue for 0.8% of the national population. [283] In 1989, Armenian was the predominant language in the Nagorno-Karabakh region, spoken by about 76% of its population. [284] Following the First Nagorno-Karabakh War, native Armenian speakers constituted around 95% of the region's population. [285]

A dozen other minority languages are spoken natively, [286] including [Avar](/Avar_language), [Budukh](/Budukh_language), [287] [Georgian](/Georgian_language), [Juhuri](/Juhuri_language), [287] [Khinalug](/Khinalug_language), [287] [Kryts](/Kryts_language), [287] [Lezgin](/Lezgian_language), [Rutul](/Rutul_language), [287] [Talysh](/Talysh_language), [Tat](/Tat_language_(Caucasus)), [287] [Tsakhur](/Tsakhur_language), [287] and [Udi](/Udi_language). [287] These languages are spoken by small minority populations, some of which are critically endangered. [288]

#### Religion

• Main articles: [Religion in Azerbaijan](/Religion_in_Azerbaijan) and [Irreligion in Azerbaijan](/Irreligion_in_Azerbaijan)

The [Bibi-Heybat Mosque](/Bibi-Heybat_Mosque) in Baku, built over the tomb of a descendant of [Muhammad](/Muhammad). [289]

Azerbaijan is recognized as the most secular Muslim-majority country. [290] Approximately 97% of the population identifies as Muslim. [291] Estimates suggest that 55–65% of Muslims are [Shia](/Shia_Islam), while 45–55% are [Sunnis](/Sunni_Muslim). [292] [293] [294] Azerbaijani Sunnis predominantly follow the [Hanafi school](/Hanafi_school). [295] [296] The secular government of Azerbaijan has officially favored a Turkish-influenced Sufi version of Sunni Islam over Shia Islam, while maintaining vigilance over the activities of all religious sects. [297] [298] Consequently, there is an observed increase in conversions to Sunni Islam, viewed as a symbol of growing ties with Turkey. [299] Other faiths are practiced by the country's diverse ethnic groups. Under Article 48 of its constitution, Azerbaijan is a [secular state](/Secular_state) that guarantees religious freedom. A poll conducted by [Gallup](/Gallup_(company)) between 2006 and 2008 found that only 21% of respondents in Azerbaijan considered religion an important part of their daily lives. [300]

Among the nation's religious minorities, the estimated 280,000 Christians (3.1%) [301] are primarily [Russian](/Russian_Orthodox_Church) and [Georgian](/Georgian_Orthodox_Church) [Orthodox](/Eastern_Orthodox_Church), along with [Armenian Apostolic](/Armenian_Apostolic_Church) adherents (most Armenians reside in the breakaway region of Nagorno-Karabakh). [26] In 2003, there were 250 [Roman Catholics](/Roman_Catholics). [302] Other Christian denominations as of 2002 included [Lutherans](/Lutheranism), [Baptists](/Baptists), and [Molokans](/Molokan). [303] A small [Protestant](/Protestant) community also exists. [304] [305] Azerbaijan is home to an ancient Jewish population with a [2,000-year history](/Mountain_Jews); Jewish organizations estimate that 12,000 Jews remain in the country, which hosts the [only Jewish-majority town](/Q%C4%B1rm%C4%B1z%C4%B1_Q%C9%99s%C9%99b%C9%99) outside of Israel and the United States. [306] [307] [308] [309] Azerbaijan also accommodates members of the [Baháʼí](/Bah%C3%A1%CA%BC%C3%AD_Faith), [Hare Krishna](/International_Society_for_Krishna_Consciousness), and [Jehovah's Witnesses](/Jehovah%27s_Witnesses) communities, as well as adherents of other religious groups. [303] Certain religious communities have reportedly faced unofficial restrictions on religious freedom. A [U.S. State Department](/U.S._State_Department) report on the matter indicated the detention of members from specific Muslim and Christian groups, and many organizations encounter difficulties in registering with the agency responsible for religious affairs, [The State Committee on Religious Associations of the Republic of Azerbaijan](/State_Committee_on_Affairs_with_Religious_Associations_of_the_Republic_of_Azerbaijan). [310]

#### Education

• Main article: [Education in Azerbaijan](/Education_in_Azerbaijan)

A classroom scene at [Dunya School](/Khazar_University).

A relatively high percentage of Azerbaijanis possess some form of higher education, particularly in scientific and technical fields. [311] During the Soviet era, literacy and average education levels saw a dramatic increase from their initial low points, despite two shifts in the standard alphabet—from [Perso-Arabic script](/Perso-Arabic_script) to [Latin](/Latin_script) in the 1920s, and from Roman to [Cyrillic](/Cyrillic) in the 1930s. According to Soviet data from 1970, literacy rates stood at 100% for both males and females aged nine to forty-nine. [311] The [United Nations Development Program](/United_Nations_Development_Program) Report of 2009 indicated a literacy rate of 99.5 percent. [312]

Since gaining independence, one of the initial legislative actions taken by Parliament was the adoption of a [modified-Latin alphabet](/Azerbaijani_alphabet) to replace the Cyrillic script, signifying a move away from Soviet influence. [313] Beyond this, the Azerbaijani education system has undergone minimal structural changes. Early reforms included the reintroduction of religious education, which had been prohibited during the Soviet period, and curriculum revisions that emphasized the use of the Azerbaijani language and eliminated ideological content. Educational institutions encompass elementary schools, thousands of preschools, general secondary schools, and [vocational schools](/Vocational_schools), including specialized secondary and technical schools. Education up to the ninth grade is compulsory. [314]

### Culture

• The [Azerbaijani carpet](/Azerbaijani_rug) and [Kalaghai](/Kalaghai), a [UNESCO](/UNESCO) [Masterpiece of Intangible Heritage of Humanity](/Masterpieces_of_the_Oral_and_Intangible_Heritage_of_Humanity).

The [culture of Azerbaijan](/Culture_of_Azerbaijan) has developed through a confluence of numerous influences, resulting in a population that is, in many respects, [bi-cultural](/Biculturalism). National traditions are preserved despite the pervasive influence of Western culture, including globalized consumerism. For instance, [Novruz Bayram](/Novruz_in_Azerbaijan), the celebration of the New Year, is a family holiday rooted in the traditional [Zoroastrianism](/Zoroastrianism) calendar. [315]

Traditional Azerbaijani attire includes the [chokha](/Chokha) and [papakhi](/Papakhi). Radio broadcasts are available in Russian, [Georgian](/Georgian_language), [Kurdish](/Kurdish_language), [Lezgian](/Lezgian_language), and [Talysh](/Talysh_language) languages, funded by the state budget. [278] Certain local radio stations in [Balakan](/Balak%C9%99n) and [Khachmaz](/Khachmaz_(city)) organize broadcasts in [Avar](/Avar_language) and [Tat](/Tat_language_(Caucasus)). [278] In Baku, several newspapers are published in Russian, Kurdish (Dengi Kurd), Lezgian (Samur), and Talysh. [278] The Jewish society "Sokhnut" publishes the newspaper Aziz. [278]

#### Architecture

[Baku White City](/Baku_White_City) in [Baku](/Baku), inaugurated in 2011 and completed in 2022.

[Azerbaijani architecture](/Architecture_of_Azerbaijan) typically blends elements of the [East](/Eastern_world) and [West](/Western_culture), [316] with significant influences from [Persian architecture](/Iranian_architecture). Numerous ancient architectural landmarks are preserved, such as the [Maiden Tower](/Maiden_Tower_(Baku)) and the [Palace of the Shirvanshahs](/Palace_of_the_Shirvanshahs) within the Walled City of Baku. Sites inscribed on the [UNESCO World Heritage](/UNESCO_World_Heritage) tentative list include the [Ateshgah of Baku](/Ateshgah_of_Baku), the [Momine Khatun Mausoleum](/Momine_Khatun_Mausoleum), [Hirkan National Park](/Hirkan_National_Park), the [Binagadi asphalt lake](/Binagadi_asphalt_lake), the [Lökbatan Mud Volcano](/L%C3%B6kbatan_Mud_Volcano), the [Shusha State Historical and Architectural Reserve](/Shusha_State_Historical_and_Architectural_Reserve), Baku Stage Mountain, Caspian Shore Defensive Constructions, Ordubad National Reserve, and the [Palace of Shaki Khans](/Palace_of_Shaki_Khans). [317] [318]

Other architectural treasures include the [Quadrangular Castle](/Quadrangular_castle_( Mardakan)) in [Mardakan](/Mardakan), [Parigala](/Parigala) in [Yukhary Chardaglar](/Yuxar%C4%B1_%C3%87ardaqlar), several bridges spanning the Aras River, and various mausoleums. Monumental architecture was limited during the 19th and early 20th centuries, though distinctive residences were constructed in Baku and other cities. Among more recent architectural achievements, the [Baku Metro](/Baku_Metro) stations are noted for their opulent decoration. [319]

The contemporary challenge for Azerbaijani architecture involves the diverse application of modern aesthetics, the pursuit of unique artistic styles, and integration with the existing historical-cultural environment. Major projects such as the [Heydar Aliyev Cultural Center](/Heydar_Aliyev_Cultural_Center), [Flame Towers](/Flame_Towers), [Baku Crystal Hall](/Baku_Crystal_Hall), [Baku White City](/Baku_White_City), and [SOCAR Tower](/SOCAR_Tower) have significantly transformed the country's skyline, promoting its modern identity. [320] [321]

#### Music and dance

[Uzeyir Hajibeyov](/Uzeyir_Hajibeyov) integrated traditional [Azerbaijani music](/Azerbaijani_music) with Western styles in the early 20th century.

[Music of Azerbaijan](/Music_of_Azerbaijan) draws upon folk traditions dating back nearly a thousand years, [322] evolving around a monodic structure and producing rhythmically diverse melodies. [323] The music features a complex modal system, where the [chromatization](/Chromaticism) of [major and minor](/Major_and_minor) [scales](/Musical_scale) holds significant importance. [323] Azerbaijan possesses a rich collection of national musical instruments, including 14 string instruments, 8 percussion instruments, and 6 wind instruments. [324] According to [The Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians](/The_New_Grove_Dictionary_of_Music_and_Musicians), "in terms of ethnicity, culture and religion the Azerbaijani are musically much closer to Iran than Turkey." [325]

[Alim Qasimov](/Alim_Qasimov) performing [mugham](/Mugham) at the [Eurovision Song Contest 2012](/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2012). The Azerbaijani Mugham tradition was inscribed by [UNESCO](/UNESCO) in 2008 as a [Masterpiece of Intangible Heritage of Humanity](/Masterpieces_of_the_Oral_and_Intangible_Heritage_of_Humanity).

[Mugham] typically consists of a suite incorporating poetry and instrumental interludes. During mugham performances, singers are expected to convey emotion through their singing and music. In contrast to the mugham traditions of Central Asian countries, Azerbaijani mugham is characterized by greater freedom of form and less rigidity, often drawing comparisons to the improvisational nature of [jazz](/Jazz). [326] [UNESCO](/UNESCO) recognized the Azerbaijani mugham tradition as a [Masterpiece of the Oral and Intangible Heritage of Humanity]. [Meykhana] refers to a distinctive traditional Azerbaijani folk singing style, typically performed unaccompanied and involving multiple individuals improvising on a given theme. [327]

[Ashiq] performances blend poetry, storytelling, dance, and vocal and instrumental music into a traditional art form that symbolizes Azerbaijani culture. It features a mystic [troubadour](/Troubadour) or traveling bard who sings and plays the [saz](/Baglama). This tradition has its roots in the [shamanistic](/Shamanism) beliefs of ancient [Turkic peoples](/Turkic_peoples). [328] Ashiqs' songs are semi-improvised, based on common themes. Azerbaijan's ashiq art was included in UNESCO's list of [Intangible Cultural Heritage] in 2009. [329]

Since the mid-1960s, Western-influenced [Azerbaijani pop music](/Azerbaijani_pop_music), in its various forms, has gained popularity in Azerbaijan, while genres like [rock](/Azerbaijani_rock) and [hip hop](/Azerbaijani_hip_hop) are widely produced and enjoyed. Azerbaijani pop and [Azerbaijani folk music](/Azerbaijani_folk_music) emerged with the international recognition of performers such as [Alim Qasimov](/Alim_Qasimov), [Rashid Behbudov](/Rashid_Behbudov), [Vagif Mustafazadeh](/Vagif_Mustafazadeh), [Muslim Magomayev](/Muslim_Magomayev_(musician)), [Shovkat Alakbarova](/Shovkat_Alakbarova), and [Rubaba Muradova](/Rubaba_Muradova). [330] Azerbaijan actively participates in the Eurovision Song Contest. Azerbaijan made its debut at the 2008 [Eurovision Song Contest](/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2008). The country's entry secured third place in 2009 and fifth place the following year. [331] [Ell and Nikki](/Eldar_%26_Nigar) won first place at the [Eurovision Song Contest 2011](/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2011) with the song "[Running Scared](/Running_Scared_(Ell_%26_Nikki_song))", granting Azerbaijan the right to host the contest in [2012](/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2012), in Baku. [332] [333] They qualified for every Grand Final until the [2018 edition of the contest](/Eurovision_Song_Contest_2018), entering with [X My Heart](/X_My_Heart_(song)) performed by singer [Aisel](/Aisel_(singer)). [334]

Dozens of [Azerbaijani folk dances](/Azerbaijani_dances) exist. These dances are performed at formal celebrations, with dancers wearing traditional attire such as the chokha, which is well-preserved within these national dances. Most dances are characterized by a very fast rhythm. [335]

#### Art

Traditional Azerbaijani clothing and musical instruments.

[Azerbaijani art](/Azerbaijani_art) is represented by a wide array of handicrafts, including [chasing](/Repouss%C3%A9_and_chasing), jeweling, metal engraving, wood, stone, or bone carving, carpet-making, lasing, pattern weaving and printing, and knitting and embroidery. Each of these decorative art forms, reflecting the nation's artistic endowments, is highly valued. Numerous merchants, travelers, and diplomats who visited the region throughout history have documented interesting facts regarding the development of arts and crafts in Azerbaijan. [336]

The [Azerbaijani carpet](/Azerbaijani_rug) is a traditional handmade textile of various sizes, characterized by a dense texture and either a pile or pile-less surface, with patterns distinctive to Azerbaijan's numerous carpet-making regions. In November 2010, the Azerbaijani carpet was proclaimed a [Masterpiece of Intangible Heritage](/Masterpieces_of_the_Oral_and_Intangible_Heritage_of_Humanity) by UNESCO. [337] [338] Azerbaijani carpets can be classified into several major groups and numerous subgroups. The scientific study of Azerbaijani carpets is closely associated with the name of [Latif Karimov](/Latif_Karimov), a prominent Soviet-era scholar and artist. [339]

Copper handwork in [Lahij](/Lah%C4%B1c,_Ismailli).

Azerbaijan has historically been recognized as a center for a wide variety of crafts. Archaeological evidence indicates well-developed agriculture, animal husbandry, metalworking, pottery, ceramics, and carpet weaving dating back to the 2nd millennium BC. Excavations at Dashbulaq, Hasansu, Zayamchai, and Tovuzchai, revealed during BTC pipeline construction, have uncovered artifacts from the early Iron Age. [340]

A [miniature painting](/Miniature_(illuminated_manuscript)) depicting a battle scene, found on the walls of the [Palace of Shaki Khans](/Palace_of_Shaki_Khans), dating from the 18th century, in the city of [Shaki](/Shaki,_Azerbaijan).

The [Gamigaya Petroglyphs], dating from the 1st to 4th millennium BC, are located in Azerbaijan's [Ordubad District](/Ordubad_District). They consist of approximately 1,500 carved rock paintings featuring images of deer, goats, bulls, dogs, snakes, birds, mythical creatures, humans, chariots, and various symbols found on basalt rocks. [341] Norwegian [ethnographer](/Ethnographer) Thor Heyerdahl proposed that people from this region migrated to [Scandinavia](/Scandinavia) around 100 AD, bringing their boatbuilding skills, which subsequently influenced the development of [Viking boats](/Longship) in Northern Europe. [342] [343]

Over centuries, Azerbaijani art has undergone numerous stylistic transformations. Painting is traditionally characterized by a warmth of color and light, as exemplified in the works of [Azim Azimzade](/Azim_Azimzade) and [Bahruz Kangarli](/Bahruz_Kangarli), with a focus on religious figures and cultural motifs. [344] Azerbaijani painting held a preeminent position in the Caucasus for centuries, spanning periods from the [Romanesque](/Romanesque_art) and [Ottoman](/Culture_of_the_Ottoman_Empire) eras through the [Soviet](/Socialist_realism) and [Baroque](/Baroque) periods, with the latter two experiencing particular development in Azerbaijan. Notable artists include [Sattar Bahlulzade](/Sattar_Bahlulzade), [Togrul Narimanbekov](/Togrul_Narimanbekov), [Tahir Salahov](/Tahir_Salahov), [Alakbar Rezaguliyev](/Alakbar_Rezaguliyev), [Mirza Gadim Iravani](/Mirza_Gadim_Iravani), [Mikayil Abdullayev](/Mikayil_Abdullayev), and [Boyukagha Mirzazade](/Boyukagha_Mirzazade). [345]

*   [Usta Gambar Karabakhi](/Usta_Gambar_Karabakhi) – Tree of Life ([Palace of Shaki Khans](/Palace_of_Shaki_Khans))
*   [Mirza Gadim Iravani](/Mirza_Gadim_Iravani) – Portrait of a sitting woman ([National Art Museum of Azerbaijan](/National_Art_Museum_of_Azerbaijan))
*   [Bahruz Kangarli](/Bahruz_Kangarli) – Landscape with mountains ([National Art Museum of Azerbaijan](/National_Art_Museum_of_Azerbaijan))
*   [Azim Azimzade](/Azim_Azimzade) – Ruins of the Reichstag ([National Art Museum of Azerbaijan](/National_Art_Museum_of_Azerbaijan))

#### Literature

The earliest known figure in written [Azerbaijani literature](/Azerbaijani_literature) was [Izzeddin Hasanoghlu](/Izzeddin_Hasanoghlu), who compiled a [divan](/Diwan_(poetry)) containing both Persian and Azerbaijani [ghazals](/Ghazal). [346] [347] In his Persian ghazals, he used a pen name, while his Azerbaijani ghazals were published under his own name, Hasanoghlu. [346] Among the medieval literary figures was the Persian poet and philosopher [Nizami](/Nizami_Ganjavi), known as Ganjavi after his birthplace, [Ganja](/Ganja,_Azerbaijan). He authored the [Khamsa](/Khamsa_of_Nizami) (The Quintuplet), a collection of five romantic poems, including "The Treasure of Mysteries," "Khosrow and Shīrīn," and "Leyli and Mejnūn." [348]

Classical literature began to take shape in the 14th century, drawing from various Early Middle Ages dialects of [Tabriz](/Tabriz) and [Shirvan](/Shirvan). Prominent poets of this era included [Gazi Burhanaddin](/Kadi_Burhan_al-Din), Haqiqi (the pen name of [Jahan Shah Qara Qoyunlu](/Jahan_Shah)), and [Habibi](/Habibi_(poet)). [349] The late 14th century marked the commencement of the literary career of [Imadaddin Nasimi](/Nesimi), [350] recognized as one of the greatest Azerbaijani [351] [352] [353] [Hurufi](/Hurufism) mystical poets of the late 14th and early 15th centuries, [354] and a leading early master of the divan in Turkic literary history. [354] Nasimi also composed poetry in Persian [352] [355] and Arabic. [354] The divan and ghazal styles were further developed by poets such as [Qasem-e Anvar](/Qasem-e_Anvar), [Fuzuli](/Fuzuli_(poet)), and the Safavid [Shah Ismail I](/Shah_Ismail_I), who wrote under the pen name "Khata'i."

The [Book of Dede Korkut] consists of two manuscripts copied in the 16th century, [356] with its composition estimated to be no earlier than the 15th century. [357] [358] It is a compilation of twelve stories reflecting the oral traditions of Oghuz nomads. [358] The 16th-century poet [Fuzuli](/Fuzuli_(poet)) produced his enduring philosophical and lyrical ghazals in Arabic, Persian, and Azerbaijani. Benefiting significantly from the rich literary heritage of his environment and building upon the legacy of his predecessors, Fuzuli emerged as the preeminent literary figure of his time. His major works include The Divan of Ghazals and The Qasidas. In the same century, Azerbaijani literature experienced further flourishing with the development of the *ashik* (Azerbaijani: Aşıq) poetic genre of bards. During this period, Shah Ismail I, writing under the pen name Khatāī (Arabic: خطائی, meaning "sinner"), composed approximately 1,400 verses in Azerbaijani, [359] which were later published as his Divan. A distinct literary style known as *qoshma* (Azerbaijani: qoşma, meaning "improvisation") was introduced and cultivated by Shah Ismail and later by his son and successor, Shah [Tahmasp I](/Tahmasp_I). [360]

Throughout the 17th and 18th centuries, Fuzuli's unique genres, alongside *ashik* poetry, were embraced by prominent poets and writers such as [Qovsi of Tabriz](/Qovsi_of_Tabriz), [Shah Abbas Sani](/Abbas_II_of_Persia), Agha Mesih Shirvani, Nishat, [Molla Vali Vidadi](/Molla_Vali_Vidadi), [Molla Panah Vagif](/Molla_Panah_Vagif), Amani, and Zafar, among others. Alongside Turks, [Turkmens](/Turkmens), and [Uzbeks](/Uzbeks), Azerbaijanis commemorate the [Epic of Koroglu] (from Azerbaijani: *kor oğlu*, meaning "blind man's son"), a legendary folk hero. [361] Several documented versions of the Koroglu epic are preserved at the Institute for Manuscripts of the [National Academy of Sciences of Azerbaijan](/National_Academy_of_Sciences_of_Azerbaijan). [347]

#### Media

• Main articles: [Media of Azerbaijan](/Media_of_Azerbaijan) and [Media freedom in Azerbaijan](/Media_freedom_in_Azerbaijan)

The first Azerbaijani newspaper, [Akinchi](/Akinchi), was published in 1875. [362] Three state-owned television channels operate: [AzTV](/AzTV), [Idman TV](/Idman_Azerbaijan_TV), and [Medeniyyet TV](/Medeniyyet_TV). There is one public channel and six private channels: [İctimai Television](/%C4%B0ctimai_Television), Space TV, [Lider TV](/Lider_TV), [Azad Azerbaijan TV](/Azad_Azerbaijan_TV), [Xazar TV](/Xazar_TV), Real TV, [363] and [ARB](/Region_TV).

#### Cinema

• Main articles: [Cinema of Azerbaijan](/Cinema_of_Azerbaijan) and [Television in Azerbaijan](/Television_in_Azerbaijan)

A scene from the Azerbaijani film [In the Kingdom of Oil and Millions](/In_the_Kingdom_of_Oil_and_Millions), 1916.

The film industry in Azerbaijan traces its origins back to 1898. Azerbaijan was among the earliest nations involved in cinematography, [364] with the first cinematic apparatus appearing in Baku. [365] In 1919, a documentary titled "The Celebration of the Anniversary of Azerbaijani Independence" was produced, commemorating the first anniversary of Azerbaijan's independence from Russia on May 27th, and premiered in June 1919 at several Baku theaters. [366] Following the establishment of Soviet power in 1920, [Nariman Narimanov], chairman of the Revolutionary Committee of Azerbaijan, signed a decree nationalizing the country's cinema industry. This also influenced the development of [Azerbaijani animation](/Azerbaijani_animation). [366]

In 1991, after Azerbaijan regained its independence from the Soviet Union, the first Baku International Film Festival East-West was held in Baku. In December 2000, former President Heydar Aliyev issued a decree designating August 2nd as the professional holiday for Azerbaijani filmmakers. Today, Azerbaijani filmmakers are once again navigating challenges similar to those faced by cinematographers prior to the Soviet Union's establishment in 1920. Both content selection and film sponsorship are largely left to the initiative of individual filmmakers. [364]

#### Cuisine

[Dolma](/Dolma), a traditional Azerbaijani meal.

[Azerbaijani cuisine](/Azerbaijani_cuisine) features a wide array of seasonal vegetables and greens. Fresh herbs, including mint, cilantro (coriander), dill, basil, parsley, tarragon, leeks, chives, thyme, marjoram, green onions, and watercress, are popular and frequently served alongside main dishes. The country's diverse climate and fertile land are reflected in its national dishes, which are based on Caspian Sea fish, local meats (primarily mutton and beef), and seasonal vegetables and greens.

Saffron-infused rice [plov](/Plov) is considered the signature dish of Azerbaijan, and [black tea](/Black_tea) is the national beverage. [367] Azerbaijanis often use traditional [armudu] (pear-shaped) glasses, indicative of a strong [tea culture](/Azerbaijani_tea_culture). [368] [369] Popular traditional dishes include [bozbash] (a lamb soup with regional variations incorporating different vegetables), [qutab] (fried turnovers filled with greens or minced meat), and [dushbara] (dumplings filled with ground meat and spices).

### Sport

• Main article: [Sport in Azerbaijan](/Sport_in_Azerbaijan)

[Shakhriyar Mamedyarov](/Shakhriyar_Mamedyarov) was the 2013 [World Rapid Chess](/World_Rapid_Chess_Championship) champion and a three-time [European Team Chess](/European_Team_Chess_Championship) champion.
[Teimour Radjabov](/Teimour_Radjabov) was the 2019 [World Cup](/Chess_World_Cup_2019) winner and a three-time European Team Chess champion.

Freestyle wrestling is traditionally regarded as Azerbaijan's [national sport](/National_sport). Since joining the [International Olympic Committee](/International_Olympic_Committee), Azerbaijan has secured fourteen Olympic medals in this discipline, including four golds. The most popular sports are [football](/Association_football) and wrestling. [370]

The [Association of Football Federations of Azerbaijan](/Association_of_Football_Federations_of_Azerbaijan), with 9,122 registered players, is the largest sporting association in the country. [371] [372] The [national football team](/Azerbaijan_national_football_team) demonstrates comparatively modest performance on the international stage, unlike the nation's football clubs. The most successful clubs include [Neftçi](/Neft%C3%A7i_PFK), [Qarabağ](/Qaraba%C4%9F_FK), and [Gabala](/Gabala_FK). In [2012](/2012%E2%80%9313_UEFA_Europa_League), Neftchi Baku became the first Azerbaijani team to advance to the group stage of a European competition. [373] [374] In [2014](/2014%E2%80%9315_UEFA_Europa_League), Qarabağ became the second Azerbaijani club to reach the group stage of the [UEFA Europa League]. In 2017, after defeating [Copenhagen](/F.C._Copenhagen) 2–2 (on [away goals](/Away_goals_rule)) in the play-off round of the [UEFA Champions League](/2017%E2%80%9318_UEFA_Champions_League), Qarabağ achieved the distinction of being the first Azerbaijani club to reach the group stage. [375]

[Futsal](/Futsal) is another sport with considerable popularity in Azerbaijan. The [Azerbaijan national futsal team](/Azerbaijan_national_futsal_team) achieved fourth place in the [2010 UEFA Futsal Championship](/2010_UEFA_Futsal_Championship), while the domestic club [Araz Naxçivan] secured bronze medals in the [2009–10 UEFA Futsal Cup](/2009%E2%80%9310_UEFA_Futsal_Cup) and the [2013–14 UEFA Futsal Cup]. [376] Azerbaijan served as the primary sponsor for the Spanish football club [Atlético de Madrid](/Atl%C3%A9tico_de_Madrid) during the 2013/2014 and 2014/2015 seasons, a partnership described by the club as intended to "promote the image of Azerbaijan in the world." [377]

Azerbaijan is recognized as one of the traditional powerhouses in the world of [chess](/Chess), [378] having hosted numerous international chess tournaments and competitions. The national team clinched the [European Team Chess Championship](/European_Team_Chess_Championship) titles in 2009, 2013, and 2017. [379] [380] [381] Notable chess players from Azerbaijan include [Teimour Radjabov](/Teimour_Radjabov), [Shahriyar Mammadyarov](/Shahriyar_Mammadyarov), [Vladimir Makogonov](/Vladimir_Makogonov), [Vugar Gashimov](/Vugar_Gashimov), and the former [World Chess Champion](/World_Chess_Champion) [Garry Kasparov](/Garry_Kasparov). As of 2014, [update] the [Shamkir Chess](/Shamkir_Chess) tournament, a Category 22 event, was one of the highest-rated chess tournaments ever held. [382] [Backgammon] also holds significant cultural importance in Azerbaijan, widely played and enjoyed by the local population. [383] [384] Various backgammon variations have been developed and analyzed by Azerbaijani experts. [385]

The [Baku National Stadium](/Baku_National_Stadium) was utilized for the inaugural [European Games](/European_Games) in June 2015.

The [Azerbaijan Women's Volleyball Super League] secured fourth place at the [2005 European Championship](/2005_Women%27s_European_Volleyball_Championship). [386] In recent years, clubs such as [Rabita Baku](/Rabita_Baku) and [Azerrail Baku](/Azerrail_Baku) have achieved considerable success in European competitions. [387] Prominent Azerbaijani volleyball players include Valeriya Korotenko, [Oksana Parkhomenko](/Oksana_Parkhomenko), Inessa Korkmaz, [Natalya Mammadova](/Natalya_Mammadova), and Alla Hasanova.

Other notable Azerbaijani athletes include [Namig Abdullayev](/Namig_Abdullayev), [Toghrul Asgarov](/Toghrul_Asgarov), [Rovshan Bayramov](/Rovshan_Bayramov), [Sharif Sharifov](/Sharif_Sharifov), [Mariya Stadnik](/Mariya_Stadnik), and Farid Mansurov in [wrestling](/Amateur_wrestling); Nazim Huseynov, [Elnur Mammadli](/Elnur_Mammadli), [Elkhan Mammadov](/Elkhan_Mammadov_(judoka)), and Rustam Orujov in judo; [Rafael Aghayev](/Rafael_Aghayev) in karate; Magomedrasul Majidov and Aghasi Mammadov in [boxing](/Boxing); Nizami Pashayev in [Olympic weightlifting](/Olympic_weightlifting); Azad Asgarov in [pankration](/Pankration); Eduard Mammadov in kickboxing; and [K-1](/K-1) fighter [Zabit Samedov](/Zabit_Samedov).

Azerbaijan features a [Formula One racetrack](/Baku_City_Circuit), constructed in 2012, [388] and hosted its first [Formula One Grand Prix](/2016_European_Grand_Prix) in 2016, [389] followed by the [Azerbaijan Grand Prix] annually since 2017. Other annual sporting events held in the country include the [Baku Cup] tennis tournament and the [Tour d'Azerbaïdjan] cycling race.

Azerbaijan has hosted several major sporting competitions since the late 2000s, including the [2013 F1 Powerboat World Championship](/2013_F1_Powerboat_World_Championship_season), the [2012 FIFA U-17 Women's World Cup](/2012_FIFA_U-17_Women%27s_World_Cup), the [2011 AIBA World Boxing Championships](/2011_AIBA_World_Boxing_Championships), the [2010 European Wrestling Championships](/2010_European_Wrestling_Championships), the [2009 Rhythmic Gymnastics European Championships](/2009_Rhythmic_Gymnastics_European_Championships), the [2014 European Taekwondo Championships](/European_Taekwondo_Championships), the [2014 Rhythmic Gymnastics European Championships](/2014_Rhythmic_Gymnastics_European_Championships), and the [2016 World Chess Olympiad](/42nd_Chess_Olympiad). [390] Baku was selected to host the [2015 European Games](/2015_European_Games). [391] Baku hosted the fourth [Islamic Solidarity Games] in 2017, [392] the [2019 European Youth Summer Olympic Festival], [393] and was a host city for [UEFA Euro 2020]. [394]

